Setting up the graphs

Journal Graph

The Journal Graph consists of all the articles published in journals in the 1990s, along with the authors who published those articles. The authors are connected to the journals via “authorship” edges. The authors alre also connected to one-another via “coauthorship” edges.

journal_graph = read.graph("../data/graphs/journals-1990s.graphml", format = "graphml")
journal_graph

We can visualize the Journal Graph to see that we have loaded something that looks like the network we expected. There are lots of nodes, they have the names of authors and articles, and there are connections among them.

plot(journal_graph, layout=layout_with_lgl, vertex.size=1, vertex.label.cex=0.2)

Coauthorship Graph

We obtain the induced subgraph of all authors (i.e. we remove articles, kept authors) in order to preserve only the edges among authors (i.e. co-authorship edges).

# filter by node_type, keep "author"
graph_all_authors = V(journal_graph)[V(journal_graph)$node_type == "author"]
co_authorship_graph = induced.subgraph(graph=journal_graph, vids=graph_all_authors)
co_authorship_graph

Main Component of Coauthorship Graph

The main component graph contains all of the authors who have some collaboration link among them.

main_component_graph = get_main_component(journal_graph)
main_component_graph
## IGRAPH 3153f0d U--- 4048 14240 -- 
## + attr: node_type (v/c), doi (v/c), issn (v/c), title (v/c), cover_date

We can inspect these graphs to verify that certain authors are present:

find_author(journal_graph, "Stone, Jeff")
## + 0/11939 vertices, from e1f39b2:
find_author(co_authorship_graph, "Stone, Jeff")
## + 0/6910 vertices, from 9dc6bd4:
find_author(main_component_graph, "Stone, Jeff")
## + 0/4048 vertices, from 3153f0d:

Article Communities

df_article_communities = get.data.frame(main_component_graph, what="vertices")
df_article_communities = df_article_communities[df_article_communities$node_type=="article",]
df_article_communities = df_article_communities[c("doi", "title", "issn", "abstract", "membership")]
df_article_communities$title = tolower(df_article_communities$title)

head(df_article_communities, n=1)
##                           doi
## 1 10.1037/0022-3514.77.6.1296
##                                                         title     issn
## 1 linguistic styles: language use as an individual difference 00223514
##                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        abstract
## 1 Can language use reflect personality style? Studies examined the reliability, factor structure, and validity of written language using a word-based, computerized text analysis program. Daily diaries from 15 substance abuse inpatients, daily writing assignments from 35 students, and journal abstracts from 40 social psychologists demonstrated good internal consistency for over 36 language dimensions. Analyses of the best 15 language dimensions from essays by 838 students yielded 4 factors that replicated across written samples from another 381 students. Finally, linguistic profiles from writing samples were compared with Thematic Apperception Test coding, self-reports, and behavioral measures from 79 students and with self-reports of a 5-factor measure and health markers from more than 1,200 students. Despite modest effect sizes, the data suggest that linguistic style is an independent and meaningful way of exploring personality.

Testing for presence of expected articles

Finding an article we expected

The article Stereotype threat effects on black and white athletic performance does appear in the communities DF, demonstrating that the code works.

sum(df_article_communities$title == "stereotype threat effects on black and white athletic performance")
## [1] 0

The article is in the journal_graph too.

V(journal_graph)[V(journal_graph)$title == "Stereotype threat effects on black and white athletic performance"]
## + 0/11939 vertices, from e1f39b2:

One articles that does not appear in DF

An article not present in the journal_graph looks like this:

V(journal_graph)[V(journal_graph)$node_type == "article" & V(journal_graph)$title == "tHis aRtiCLe doEs NoT ExISt"]
## + 0/11939 vertices, from e1f39b2:

The article Construction of Circumplex Scales for the Inventory of Interpersonal Problems is present in the journal_graph but not the article_communities.

V(journal_graph)[V(journal_graph)$node_type == "article" & V(journal_graph)$title == "Construction of Circumplex Scales for the Inventory of Interpersonal Problems"]
## + 1/11939 vertex, from e1f39b2:
## [1] 5485

We can look at the communities df and it is not there.

sum(df_article_communities$title == "construction of circumplex scales for the inventory of interpersonal problems")
## [1] 1

Other articles that do not appear in DF

Quite a few articles are missing. These articles are present in journal_graph - but not in these communities.
